"""Mock Interview: Security Automation Platform — Two-voice dialogue."""


def build():
    lines = []

    # SECTION 1: Requirements (~5 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Hi, welcome. Today I'd like you to design a Security Automation Platform — think a CVE management system with AI-powered diagnosis. Teams are drowning in scanner reports from SAST, DAST, SCA, and container scanning tools, and we want to automate the triage, diagnosis, and remediation workflow so that developers wake up to a dashboard where everything's already triaged, fixes are suggested, and one-click remediation is possible. Start by clarifying the requirements."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Thanks. This is a domain I'm excited about because the problem is real — I've seen teams spend 45 minutes triaging a single CVE, and most of that time is grunt work. The first question I need to answer is about the scanner ecosystem. Which scanner types are we integrating, and are we standardizing on a single vendor per category or supporting multiple? Because integrating Veracode for SAST, Anchore for container scanning, and a DAST tool like ZAP gives us very different data formats and workflows than a single vendor suite."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "We integrate multiple scanner types across categories: SAST — think Veracode, Semgrep; DAST — ZAP, Burp; SCA — Snyk, Dependabot; and container scanning — Anchore, Trivy. We don't standardize on one vendor per category — teams use different tools and we need to ingest them all. Each scanner produces its own format, though many support SARIF as an interchange."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "OK, so multi-scanner, multi-vendor, with SARIF as a common denominator but not the only format. Next I'd want to understand the team roles and their workflows. You mentioned developers, image maintainers, and release managers — each probably cares about different subsets of findings. A developer cares about SAST and SCA findings in their codebase. An image maintainer cares about container scan results for their base images. A release manager cares about the aggregate risk posture before a release goes out. Are we designing separate views per role, or a single view with role-based filtering?"))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Both — role-tailored dashboards as the default view, with the ability to drill into any finding regardless of role. Developers see their open findings grouped by repo and severity. Image maintainers see CVEs affecting their base images with upgrade paths. Release managers see a release-readiness score with blocking issues highlighted. But any role can search and view any finding — roles affect the default view, not access control."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "That's a good model — role-based views for efficiency, not for restriction. Now let me ask about the lifecycle. You mentioned Scan, Triage, Assign, Remediate, Verify, Close. Is that the canonical lifecycle for every finding, and are there state transitions that require human approval versus ones that can be automated? For instance, can the AI auto-close a finding it determines is a false positive, or does that always need human confirmation?"))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "The lifecycle is canonical for every finding. Auto-close is allowed for findings the AI classifies as false positive with confidence above 95 percent — but only for low and informational severity. Medium and above always need human confirmation even if the AI is 99 percent confident it's a false positive. The AI can auto-assign, auto-suggest fixes, and auto-verify fixes for low-severity findings. Everything else requires human confirmation at the appropriate step."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "That's a sensible trust model. Last question on requirements: compliance and audit trail. Are we building this for a regulated environment — SOC 2, ISO 27001, PCI-DSS — where every triage decision, every false positive dismissal, and every remediation action must be traceable? Because that changes what we store and how long we store it."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Yes, this is a SOC 2 and ISO 27001 environment. Every state transition on a finding must be auditable: who or what made the decision, what evidence supported it, when it happened, and what the previous state was. We need 7-year retention on all finding history and triage decisions. The audit trail is not optional — it's a compliance requirement."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Let me summarize. We're building a Security Automation Platform that ingests reports from multiple scanner types — SAST, DAST, SCA, container — from multiple vendors. SARIF as a common format. Role-tailored dashboards for developers, image maintainers, and release managers. Canonical lifecycle: Scan, Triage, Assign, Remediate, Verify, Close. AI can auto-triage and auto-close low-severity false positives above 95 percent confidence. Medium and above need human confirmation. Full audit trail with 7-year retention for SOC 2 and ISO 27001 compliance. Let me move to estimation."))

    # SECTION 2: Estimation (~5 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Go ahead with the numbers."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Let me start with scanner throughput. With, say, 200 active repos, each running SAST on every PR and a full scan nightly, that's maybe 200 PR scans per day plus 200 nightly scans — 400 SAST scan runs. Each SAST scan might produce 20 to 50 findings on average, so roughly 8,000 to 20,000 SAST findings per day. But most of those are duplicates from the same code — the same vulnerability persists across scans until it's fixed. Unique new findings per day might be 500 to 1,000."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "SCA is similar but findings are more stable — maybe 5 to 15 per repo, so 1,000 to 3,000 per day with 200 to 500 new. DAST runs weekly, maybe 20 scans per week with 30 to 100 findings each. Container scans on every image build — 500 builds per day, each with 10 to 40 CVEs, so 5,000 to 20,000 container findings per day with 1,000 to 3,000 new."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Total raw volume: 15,000 to 40,000 findings per day. After deduplication — merging the same CVE reported by different scanners on the same artifact — maybe 1,500 to 3,000 truly new findings per day. At 45 minutes per manual triage, that's 1,125 to 2,250 person-hours daily — infeasible. At 5 minutes with AI assistance, 125 to 250 person-hours. Manageable across a team."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "What about storage for all the finding data?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Each finding record is substantial. The core fields — finding ID, scanner source, CVE or CWE identifier, severity, affected artifact, file path, line range, and status — are maybe 500 bytes. The SARIF-formatted scanner output for a single finding can be 2 to 5 KB with the full rule metadata, message strings, and location details. The AI diagnosis — root cause analysis, suggested fix, confidence score, and reasoning — adds maybe 1 to 2 KB. The remediation suggestion — patch diff, dependency upgrade path, or code snippet — is another 1 to 3 KB. And the audit trail per finding across its lifecycle is maybe 2 KB on average, growing with each state transition. So a fully processed finding is about 6 to 15 KB. Let's call it 10 KB average."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "At 3,000 new deduplicated findings per day, that's 30 MB daily, about 77 GB over 7 years. Raw scanner output is larger — 40,000 raw findings at 3 KB each is 120 MB daily, 300 GB over 7 years. Full SARIF scan results are bigger still — 5 to 50 MB per scan, 400 scans per day, so 2 to 20 GB daily. We'd keep raw scan results hot for 90 days and archive to cold storage, retaining only extracted findings long-term. Hot storage around 500 GB, cold for 7-year compliance is 10 to 50 TB. Manageable with object storage tiering."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "And the AI pipeline — what's the compute demand for overnight diagnosis?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The overnight AI diagnosis runs on 1,500 to 3,000 new findings. Each involves a few model calls — false positive classification, root cause analysis, fix suggestion — roughly 2,000 input tokens and 1,000 output tokens per finding. At 3,000 findings, that's 6M input and 3M output tokens daily. Using a capable model at roughly 30 dollars per million input and 60 per million output, that's about 360 dollars per day, or 130K per year. The 80 percent workload reduction justifies it. Cheaper models for simpler tasks like false positive classification bring the cost down further."))

    # SECTION 3: High-Level Architecture (~5 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Good. Let's move to the high-level architecture."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Here's the overall design. Scanners push results to an Ingestion Gateway, which accepts SARIF, SPDX, and vendor-specific formats via webhooks and file uploads. The Ingestion Gateway normalizes everything into our internal finding model and writes to the Finding Store — a database that holds the canonical record for every finding, with its lifecycle state, deduplication metadata, and audit trail. Before writing, the Deduplication Engine checks whether this finding already exists — same CVE on the same artifact with the same version range — and if so, updates the existing record with the new scan reference rather than creating a duplicate."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "From the Finding Store, new and changed findings flow into the AI Triage Pipeline. This is the overnight batch process that does three things per finding: false positive classification, root cause analysis with CWE mapping, and fix suggestion generation. The pipeline is orchestrated by a workflow engine — think Step Functions or Temporal — that runs each finding through the three stages sequentially, with the output of each stage available to the next. The pipeline writes its results back to the Finding Store and updates the finding's state from NEW to TRIAGED."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Once triaged, the Assignment Engine routes findings to the right team or individual based on the affected artifact. SAST findings go to the code owner of the affected file — we can pull this from the repo's CODEOWNERS file. SCA findings go to the team that owns the dependency file — package.json, go.sum, etc. Container findings go to the image maintainer for the affected base image. DAST findings go to the service team that owns the endpoint. The Assignment Engine writes the assignee to the Finding Store and updates state to ASSIGNED."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The Dashboard Service serves role-tailored views. Developers see their assigned findings grouped by repo and severity. Image maintainers see CVEs affecting their images with available base image upgrades. Release managers see a release-readiness dashboard with a risk score and blocking findings. All views are read from the Finding Store, with materialized aggregates for the dashboard metrics. And a Discussion Bot is embedded in the dashboard — when a developer clicks on a finding, they can chat with the bot about the root cause, ask for alternative fixes, or request a second opinion on the false positive classification."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Where does one-click remediation fit in?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "One-click remediation is the most impactful feature. When the AI suggests a fix — say, upgrading a dependency from 2.3.1 to 2.3.4 — the platform generates a ready-to-merge PR. The developer clicks 'Apply Fix,' and the system forks the repo, applies the patch, runs the scanner to verify the fix, and opens a PR with changelog and CVE details. The developer reviews and merges. The fix PR is not a blind auto-merge — it's a well-documented, pre-verified PR. If the scanner still reports the finding after the fix, it's flagged as 'fix unsuccessful' and the developer can try an alternative or escalate."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "What about pull request integration — flagging weaknesses before merge?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "PR integration is the shift-left piece. When a PR opens, the scanner runs on the changed code and posts findings as inline comments — severity, CWE, suggested fix. The PR isn't blocked by default, but release managers can configure blocking rules: 'Block PRs that introduce Critical or High SAST findings.' When a developer dismisses a finding with a reason — 'test file,' 'sanitized upstream' — that reason feeds back into the false positive classifier. Over time, the AI learns the team's patterns. This is the feedback loop that makes the system smarter."))

    # SECTION 4: Deep Dive — AI Diagnosis Pipeline and Remediation Workflow (~10 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Let's deep dive into the AI diagnosis pipeline. How does it work in detail?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The AI Triage Pipeline runs overnight as a batch job, but it's also triggered on-demand for high-severity findings that come in during the day. The pipeline has three stages per finding, and each stage has a specific model call with a carefully designed prompt."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Stage 1 is False Positive Classification. The model receives the finding's full context: scanner type, rule ID, CVE or CWE identifier, the affected code snippet — up to 50 lines around the finding — the file path, and the scanner's confidence score. The prompt asks the model to classify the finding as 'genuine,' 'false_positive,' or 'needs_review,' with a confidence score. The model also provides a reasoning chain — why it believes the finding is genuine or false. For example: 'This SQL injection finding in a DAO layer is genuine because the concatenated string is built from user input at line 42 with no parameterization.' Or: 'This XSS finding is a false positive because the output is already escaped by the template engine at line 38.' The reasoning is stored in the audit trail."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Stage 2 is Root Cause Analysis and CWE Mapping. For genuine findings, the model analyzes the vulnerability pattern and maps it to the most specific CWE. A scanner might report 'SQL Injection' generically, but the root cause might be CWE-89 — SQL Injection — or more specifically CWE-564 — SQL Injection through HTTP variables — or CWE-20 — Improper Input Validation leading to injection. The more specific the CWE, the better the fix suggestion. The model also identifies the root cause: where exactly the untrusted data enters, how it flows to the vulnerable sink, and what sanitization or validation is missing. This root cause trace is presented on the dashboard so the developer understands not just what's wrong but why."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Stage 3 is Fix Suggestion. Given the root cause and CWE, the model generates a concrete fix. For SAST findings, it proposes a code change — adding parameterized queries, escaping output, adding input validation. For SCA findings, it identifies the minimum safe version of the vulnerable dependency and checks whether that version is compatible with the project's other dependencies. For container findings, it identifies the base image version that patches the CVE. The fix suggestion includes a confidence score and a risk assessment — 'this dependency upgrade has no known breaking changes' versus 'this major version upgrade may require code changes.'"))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "How do you handle the case where the AI hallucinates a fix? Like suggesting a function that doesn't exist in the codebase?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "This is the most dangerous failure mode in the pipeline, and we defend against it at multiple levels. First, for code fix suggestions, we don't just take the model's output and generate a PR. We run the suggested fix through a validation step: we apply the fix to a checkout of the repo, run the linter and type checker, and run the relevant scanner. If the fix doesn't compile, the type checker fails, or the scanner still reports the finding, the fix is marked as 'unverified' and the developer is warned that the AI suggestion may not be correct. Second, we check that the suggested code references actually exist in the codebase — function names, class names, import paths. The model might suggest calling a sanitize() function that doesn't exist. A quick AST check against the codebase catches this. Third, for dependency upgrades, we verify against the actual package registry that the suggested version exists and that it doesn't introduce new vulnerabilities — we cross-reference our own vulnerability database."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The key principle is that AI suggestions are always verified before they're presented as actionable. An unverified suggestion is clearly labeled — 'AI-suggested fix, not verified. Manual review recommended.' A verified suggestion — one that passes the compilation check, the scanner check, and the reference check — gets a higher confidence badge. This distinction is crucial for building developer trust. If we present hallucinated fixes as confidently as verified fixes, developers will stop trusting the system and go back to manual triage."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Tell me more about the false positive management and patterns. How does the system learn from feedback?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "False positive management has two components: per-finding classification and pattern learning. Per-finding classification is the Stage 1 pipeline I described — the AI classifies each finding individually. Pattern learning is the meta-layer that makes the system smarter over time. When a human overrides the AI's classification — confirming a false positive that the AI marked as genuine, or vice versa — that override is a training signal. We collect these overrides with the human's reason and feed them into two feedback loops."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The first loop is the prompt refinement loop. If developers consistently override false positive classifications for a specific scanner rule — like a Veracode rule that flags certain logging patterns as information exposure — we update the Stage 1 prompt to include this pattern as a known false positive. The prompt might say: 'Rule ID VERACODE-3124 on logging statements is commonly a false positive when the logged data does not contain sensitive information. Consider whether the logged variables include PII or credentials before classifying.' This is lightweight prompt engineering, not full model fine-tuning, and it can be deployed quickly."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The second loop is the suppression rule generator. When a pattern of false positives is identified — say, 50 overrides where developers say 'this is a test file' — the system can propose a suppression rule: 'Auto-suppress findings in files matching *_test.go when the rule is CWE-89.' A security engineer reviews and approves the suppression rule, and from then on, matching findings are auto-suppressed without going through the AI pipeline. This is the 80 percent workload reduction in action — if we can suppress known false positive patterns, the human triage workload drops dramatically."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Let's talk about transitive dependencies. How does the SCA workflow handle the 'invisible risk' problem?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Transitive dependencies are the hardest part of SCA because the vulnerability is in a package the developer never directly imported. Your project depends on library A, which depends on library B, which depends on library C with CVE-2024-1234. The developer's package.json only lists A. When the scanner reports CVE-2024-1234, the developer sees a vulnerability in a package they've never heard of and doesn't know how to fix it — upgrading C directly might break B, and they don't control B's dependency choices."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Our SCA workflow handles this with a dependency resolution tree. When we ingest an SCA finding, we resolve the full dependency graph — not just the direct dependencies, but the transitive chain. We identify the path from the project's direct dependency down to the vulnerable package. Then we check whether there's a version of any package in the chain that both patches the vulnerability and is compatible with the rest of the tree. Maybe upgrading B from 2.1 to 2.2 pulls in C 3.5 which patches the CVE, and B 2.2 is backward-compatible with A. Our fix suggestion would be: 'Upgrade B from 2.1 to 2.2. This pulls in C 3.5, which patches CVE-2024-1234. B 2.2 has no known breaking changes.' If no clean upgrade path exists, we flag it as 'requires manual resolution' and suggest the developer reach out to the maintainer of the intermediate package — or consider replacing the dependency altogether."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "We also show the dependency tree visually on the dashboard — a small graph showing the path from the developer's direct dependency down to the vulnerable package. This is important because without seeing the chain, a developer might try to upgrade C directly, which gets overwritten the next time B is installed. The visual makes the transitive relationship clear and prevents that common mistake."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Walk me through the SecGate shadow mode scanner. How does it work alongside commercial tools?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "SecGate is our custom scanner that runs in shadow mode — it ingests the same code and artifacts as the commercial scanners, produces its own findings, but doesn't surface them to developers directly. Instead, we compare SecGate's findings against the commercial scanners' findings. The 96 percent match rate means that for 96 percent of SecGate's findings, at least one commercial scanner also reported the same vulnerability. The remaining 4 percent are findings SecGate caught that all commercial scanners missed."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "These delta findings are high-value — they represent vulnerabilities that would otherwise go undetected. We surface them separately on a 'SecGate Exclusive' dashboard for security engineers to review. Because SecGate is a custom tool, its findings carry less trust than commercial scanner findings — the false positive rate might be higher. So we don't auto-triage these through the same pipeline. Instead, a security engineer manually reviews each SecGate-exclusive finding, and if confirmed, it enters the normal triage pipeline with an 'escalated by security engineer' audit entry. Over time, as we validate SecGate's accuracy, we can increase its trust level and start auto-triaging its findings."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "SecGate also serves as a quality check on the commercial scanners. If commercial scanners consistently miss a category SecGate catches, that's a signal to reconfigure or add a tool. We run the delta analysis monthly and track the match rate — if it drops from 96 to 90 percent, something's changing in scanner coverage or vulnerability patterns."))

    # SECTION 5: Failure Modes (~4 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "What are the most critical failure scenarios?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The first and most obvious is a scanner outage. If Veracode goes down, SAST findings stop flowing for the repos that depend on it. This is partially mitigated by multi-vendor coverage — if we have both Veracode and Semgrep for SAST, a Veracode outage only affects repos that use Veracode exclusively. But for repos that only use one scanner, we have a gap. Our response is to flag the gap on the release manager's dashboard — 'SAST coverage incomplete for repo X due to scanner outage' — so that releases from that repo can be held until coverage resumes. We also cache the last known scan results and use them as the baseline, clearly marked as stale with the scan timestamp."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The second failure is AI hallucination on fix suggestions, which we discussed. But there's a more subtle variant: the AI confidently misclassifies a genuine vulnerability as a false positive — a false negative. This is worse than a hallucinated fix because it's invisible. The developer never sees the finding because it was auto-closed. We mitigate this in three ways. First, as I said, auto-close only for low-severity findings above 95 percent confidence. Medium and above always get human review. Second, we run a weekly false negative audit — a sample of auto-closed findings is reviewed by a security engineer. Third, the SecGate shadow scanner acts as an independent check. If SecGate reports a finding that the AI pipeline auto-closed as a false positive, that's a flag for manual review."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The third failure is a data consistency issue — the same finding reported by two scanners with conflicting severity ratings. Veracode might call it High, Semgrep might call it Medium. Our deduplication engine needs a severity reconciliation strategy. We use the highest severity across all scanners as the canonical severity, because under-triageing is worse than over-triageing. A finding that's genuinely High but triaged as Medium might get deferred, while a finding that's genuinely Medium but triaged as High just gets slightly more attention than it needs. The conservative choice is to surface the highest severity and let the triage process adjust."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The fourth failure is a more systemic one: the feedback loop degrades. If developers stop providing override reasons — they just click 'dismiss' without explaining why — the pattern learning stops working. The AI's false positive classification accuracy slowly degrades, and the workload reduction drops from 80 percent to, say, 60 percent. This is a product and UX problem, not a technical one. We need to make providing feedback frictionless — maybe a quick-select of common reasons like 'test file,' 'false positive,' 'already mitigated,' 'risk accepted' — and we need to show developers the impact of their feedback: 'Your overrides have prevented 47 similar false positives this month.' Making the feedback loop visible and rewarding is critical for maintaining it."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "What about the SARIF ingestion pipeline itself — what if a malformed SARIF file comes in?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The Ingestion Gateway validates every incoming file against the SARIF JSON schema. If validation fails, the file is quarantined and an alert is sent to the integration owner. We also validate semantic correctness: required locations, valid severity values, well-formed CVE identifiers. Vendor-specific converters have their own validation and integration tests, rerun when scanner vendors update their output formats."))

    # SECTION 6: Scale & Debrief (~3 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "How does the design change at 10x scale — multi-org, multi-scanner, 10x volume?"))

    lines.append(("candidate", "At 10x, we're looking at 2,000 repos, 30,000 to 50,000 raw findings per day, and multiple organizations with their own scanner configs, roles, and compliance requirements. The Finding Store is sharded by org ID. The AI Pipeline needs parallelization — at 30,000 findings per overnight batch and 7 seconds each, that's 58 hours serially. With 50 concurrent workers, wall time drops to about 10 minutes."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "The deduplication engine becomes a bottleneck. With millions of existing findings, we'd build a deduplication index keyed on a hash of CVE ID, artifact identifier, and version range — constant-time lookup in Redis, with a follow-up comparison only on hash match."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Multi-scanner at 10x means 20 integrations instead of 8. We'd invest in a scanner integration SDK with common validation, transformation, and testing scaffolding, so adding a scanner is configuration rather than development."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Compliance is more complex — different orgs have SOC 2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA, FedRAMP, each with different remediation SLAs and reporting requirements. A compliance rules engine maps finding severity and category to the applicable SLA per org and per scope. A Critical CVE in PCI-DSS scope might have a 30-day SLA versus 90 days in a non-PCI scope."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "At 0.1x — 20 repos, 200 findings per day — a single database handles the Finding Store, the AI pipeline runs on a small instance, and SQL suffices for deduplication. But the core pipeline — Ingestion, Deduplication, AI Triage, Assignment, Remediation — stays the same. Even at 20 repos, you need deduplication, AI triage, and the audit trail. The lifecycle is the same regardless of scale."))

    # SECTION 7: End-to-End Walkthrough (~4 min)
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Walk me through the complete trace of a CVE from scanner detection to one-click fix."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Let's trace CVE-2024-5678, a High severity SQL injection in the payments service. Step 1: Detection. The nightly Veracode SAST scan on the payments-service repo finishes at 2 AM and uploads its SARIF results to the Ingestion Gateway. The SARIF file contains 23 findings, including one at line 42 of PaymentDAO.java. The rule is 'SQL Injection' with Veracode confidence 95. The Gateway validates the SARIF, normalizes the finding, and calls the Deduplication Engine."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 2: Deduplication. The Engine hashes the tuple — CVE not assigned yet, so it uses CWE-89 + PaymentDAO.java + lines 40-45 — and checks the deduplication index. No match found — this is a new finding. The Engine creates a new finding record in the Finding Store with ID FND-78432, status NEW, severity HIGH, scanner source VERACODE-SAST, CWE-89, affected artifact payments-service/PaymentDAO.java:42, and the full SARIF detail. The audit trail logs: {timestamp: 02:15:33Z, action: CREATED, actor: INGESTION_GATEWAY, evidence: VERACODE_SARIF_RUN_9876}."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 3: AI Triage. At 3 AM, the overnight batch picks up FND-78432. Stage 1 — False Positive Classification: the model receives the code context around line 42, which shows string concatenation in a SQL query with an unparameterized input from a request object. The model classifies it as GENUINE with confidence 0.97. Stage 2 — Root Cause Analysis: the model identifies the root cause as CWE-89, with the tainted data entering at line 38 from request.getParameter('accountId'), flowing through a string builder, and reaching the SQL execute at line 42 without parameterization. Stage 3 — Fix Suggestion: the model suggests replacing the concatenated query with a PreparedStatement, using setString(1, accountId). The fix confidence is 0.91. The pipeline writes all three stage outputs to the Finding Store and updates the finding status to TRIAGED. Audit trail: {timestamp: 03:07:12Z, action: TRIAGED, actor: AI_PIPELINE, evidence: {fp_classification: GENUINE/0.97, root_cause: CWE-89, fix_suggestion: PreparedStatement/0.91, reasoning: '...'}}."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 4: Assignment. The Assignment Engine resolves the code owner for PaymentDAO.java via the repo's CODEOWNERS file — it's the payments-backend team, specifically user @alice. The finding is assigned to alice and status moves to ASSIGNED. Audit trail: {timestamp: 03:07:13Z, action: ASSIGNED, actor: ASSIGNMENT_ENGINE, evidence: {assignee: 'alice', reason: 'CODEOWNERS PaymentDAO.java'}}."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 5: Morning Dashboard. Alice logs in at 9 AM and sees FND-78432 on her developer dashboard under 'High Severity — Requires Attention.' She clicks it and sees the full triage: the code snippet with the vulnerability highlighted, the root cause trace showing the tainted data flow, the AI's genuine classification with reasoning, and the suggested PreparedStatement fix. She clicks 'Discuss with Bot' and asks, 'Is the accountId always coming from user input, or is it sometimes from internal calls?' The Discussion Bot analyzes the callers of PaymentDAO and responds: 'accountId is passed from PaymentService.processPayment, which receives it from the HTTP request body. It's always user-controlled.' This confirms the vulnerability is genuine."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 6: One-Click Remediation. Alice clicks 'Apply Fix.' The system forks the payments-service repo, applies the PreparedStatement change suggested by the AI pipeline, runs the Veracode SAST scan on the branch, and the scan confirms the finding is no longer present. A PR is opened with the title 'Fix SQL Injection in PaymentDAO — CVE-2024-5678' and includes the code change, the CVE details, and the scan verification result. Alice reviews the PR — it's a clean, single-line change from string concatenation to PreparedStatement — and clicks Merge. The finding status moves to REMEDIATED. Audit trail: {timestamp: 09:23:41Z, action: REMEDIATED, actor: 'alice', evidence: {fix_pr: 'PR-456', scanner_verification: PASS}}."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Step 7: Verify and Close. After merge, the nightly scan no longer reports the finding. The Verification Engine detects FND-78432 is absent from the latest scan, updates status to VERIFIED then CLOSED. Total time from detection to closure: ~24 hours, with about 5 minutes of Alice's active time — down from the 45-minute baseline."))

    # SECTION 8: Thinking Process & Beats (~3 min) — interviewer monologue
    lines.append(("interviewer", "Let me close with my thinking process for evaluating security automation designs. I start with pipeline architecture — the platform is a data pipeline: ingest, enrich, triage, route, remediate, verify. The pipeline must be idempotent, replayable, and have independently deployable stages. If the false positive classifier needs a prompt update, I should deploy that without touching the fix suggestion. A candidate who designs the pipeline as a single monolithic model call is missing this beat."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "The second beat is the trust model around AI triage. The AI is a recommendation engine, not the decision-maker. Humans make the final call above low severity. The 80 percent workload reduction comes from the AI handling obvious cases and surfacing only ambiguous ones. A candidate who auto-closes medium-severity findings will miss real vulnerabilities. The trust model must be explicit, configurable, and conservative by default."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "The third beat is false positive management as a first-class system. False positives are why teams lose trust in scanners. Without aggressive management — AI classification, pattern-based suppression, feedback loops — the dashboard becomes noise and developers stop looking. The feedback loop is critical: a system that learns from overrides gets better; one that doesn't gets worse relative to the evolving codebase. I look for candidates who design the loop explicitly — how overrides are collected, how they inform prompts, how they generate suppression rules, and how the system measures its own accuracy."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "The fourth beat is the audit trail. In compliance, it's the product. Every triage decision must be auditable with evidence — not just what happened but why. When an auditor asks why a CVE was closed, the answer must include the AI's reasoning, the human's confirmation, and the timestamp. A simple log table is not compliance. The audit trail must be structured, queryable, and retention-managed from day one."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Then there are the traps. Trap one: trusting AI blindly. Auto-closing a genuine vulnerability creates a false sense of security. The defense is layered trust — low-severity-only auto-close, human confirmation above that, and SecGate as independent verification. Trap two: ignoring transitive dependencies. A candidate who says 'upgrade the vulnerable package' without resolving the dependency tree doesn't understand how package managers work. The fix must be at the correct level in the chain, and visual dependency trees are essential correctness tooling, not a nice UI feature. Trap three: no feedback loop. Without a mechanism to collect overrides and feed them back, the 80 percent workload reduction degrades to 60, then 40, and the system becomes just another scanner developers ignore."))

    lines.append(("interviewer", "Let me give you my overall assessment. Positives: requirements clarification was thorough — multi-scanner support, role-based views, and the auto-close trust model were unprompted. The SecGate shadow scanner design is sophisticated — using an independent scanner as a quality check on both commercial tools and the AI pipeline is a pattern I haven't seen many candidates propose. Your transitive dependency analysis with visual dependency trees and upgrade path resolution is spot on. The end-to-end walkthrough made the value proposition concrete. For improvement: OWASP Top 10 awareness could have been addressed more explicitly — mapping findings to OWASP categories gives release managers a more meaningful risk view than raw CVE counts. And one-click remediation's interaction with CI/CD policies deserved more attention — some orgs require two-person review, and auto-generated PRs must respect those policies. Overall, very strong. Thanks."))

    lines.append(("candidate", "Thank you. You're right about OWASP Top 10 mapping — that's a natural layer on top of CWE classification that gives non-security stakeholders a familiar risk framework. And CI/CD policy integration is critical — the auto-generated PR must go through the same approval gates as any other PR, including two-person review where required. The one-click remediation automates the fix generation, not the fix approval. I appreciate the feedback."))

    return lines
